{"cursor":"7507","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Optical rotation (optical activity)' is the turning of the plane of linearly\npolarized light about the direction of motion as the light travels through\ncertain materials. It occurs in solutions of chiral molecules such as sucrose\n(sugar), solids with rotated crystal planes such as quartz, and spin-polarized\ngases of atoms or molecules. It is used in the sugar industry to measure syrup\nconcentration, in optics to manipulate polarization, in chemistry to\ncharacterize substances in solution, and in optical mineralogy to help identify\ncertain minerals in thin sections. It is being developed as a method to measure\nblood sugar concentration in diabetic people.\n","linknr":206,"url":"Optical_activity","recorded":1362581317,"links":31,"instances":["fermentation","waves","optics","chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Polarization","Stereochemistry"],"headings":["History","Theory","Areas of use","References","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/TartrateCrystal.svg/200px-TartrateCrystal.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/c/0dc820b56b6ca1a25e48436ad916f2e2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/e/b/5eb237ccb8c2716d347ab313cad7918e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/a/d/4ad483e7014e263d7dd71552bf3c3a50.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/d/7/3d7e996adfe310516ca31c796df1ce8c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/4/a/04afb540a2a5967188c641125b081f20.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/2/0/d20caec3b48a1eef164cb4ca81ba2587.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/f/5/1f559213cac5dfa72c2949e580469d0f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/0/5/e05a30d96800384dd38b22851322a6b5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/1/9/519aeb45c0f9f4371b62b0a0f7c82bd1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/2/0/d20caec3b48a1eef164cb4ca81ba2587.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/f/5/5f57f9ea3b04c517e5af710d5cf42ca7.png","//uploa